is is the same problem that exists for any shared git branch (like `entire/checkpoints/v1`). The checkpoint store uses git plumbing operations — it reads the current tip of the branch, builds a new tree, and creates a commit with the old tip as parent. If two processes race, they'd both create commits with the same parent, and the second one to update the ref would win, orphaning the first one's commit.\\n\\nGit ref updates can be made atomic with compare-and-swap operations, though I'm not sure if the current code leverages this. The real question is whether this race condition is likely in practice and whether Approach A makes it worse. Two concurrent processes would only conflict if they're both modifying the same trail's metadata simultaneously from different worktrees, which seems unlikely. Approach B reduces conflicts by splitting branch entries into separate files, but the branch index itself becomes a bottleneck. Approach C avoids conflicts entirely since different branches write to different paths. In practice though, the risk feels low since concurrent modifications to the same trail are rare.\\n\\nTrail metadata updates happen infrequently, checkpoint appending is bounded by commit frequency, and the git ref update window is narrow. I think Approach A is still acceptable for now, though we could add retry-on-conflict logic, file locking, or leverage git's compare-and-swap for safer ref updates if needed.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1688,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":36780,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1688},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYnixmjcs6TWY7n4kSUrm\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"94d405c0-07e9-4640-b115-5449d756e8c8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T23:51:30.938Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"94d405c0-07e9-4640-b115-5449d756e8c8\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"sessionId\":\"cc5ed6bd-0c2c-4c91-94f7-7c18e3bda941\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/trails-multi-pr\",\"slug\":\"jazzy-inventing-fern\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01CudkcrwcPQnmsdMc9ynece\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Sharp instinct — yes, this is a real concern. The trail data lives on `entire/trails/v1` (an orphan branch), and writes are: read tip → build new tree → commit → update ref. Two concurrent processes hitting the same trail could race:\\n\\n1. Session A reads metadata (branches: [X])\\n2. Session B reads metadata (branches: [X])\\n3. Session A writes (branches: [X, Y])\\n4. Session B writes (branches: [X, Z]) — **clobbers Y**\\n\\n**How bad is it in practice with Approach A?**\\n\\nThe risky operations are:\\n- **Adding a branch to a trail** — explicit user action, unlikely to race\\n- **Appending a checkpoint** — happens on commit, could race if two worktrees commit simultaneously on branches belonging to the same trail\\n- **Updating PR reference** — explicit user action, unlikely to race\\n\\nSo checkpoint appending is the main risk. And with multi-branch trails, you're *more likely* to have concurrent sessions on different branches of the same trail — that's the whole point.\\n\\n**Mitigation options (cheapest to most complex):**\\n\\n1. **Optimistic concurrency via `git update-ref --stdin`** — use compare-and-swap on the ref. If the ref moved since we read it, re-read and retry. Narrow retry loop, no locks. This is git-native.\\n\\n2. **Approach C's subdirectory structure just for checkpoints** — branch entries live in metadata.json (rarely updated), but checkpoints append to `branches/<branch-id>/checkpoints.json`. Different branches write to different paths, reducing conflicts.\\n\\n3. **File locking** — lockfile in `.git/` before trail writes. Works but adds coordination overhead.\\n\\nI'd lean toward **(1) optimistic concurrency** as the baseline — it's the git-native way and handles the general case. We might not even need (2) if retries are cheap.\\n\\nDoes the concurrency concern change your thinking on the approach, or is optimistic retry sufficient?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1688,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":36780,\"output_tokens\":1111,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1688,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYnixmjcs6TWY7n4kSUrm\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"65d232e9-0f6a-465a-bc5b-437b411cab03\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T23:51:39.365Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"65d232e9-0f6a-465a-bc5b-437b411cab03\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"sessionId\":\"cc5ed6bd-0c2c-4c91-94f7-7c18e3bda941\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/trails-multi-pr\",\"slug\":\"jazzy-inventing-fern\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"e4420d45-21d1-4b3c-a30d-d76c620553d9\",\"toolUseID\":\"e4420d45-21d1-4b3c-a30d-d76c620553d9\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-06T23:51:39.398Z\",\"uuid\":\"ee4b6906-50ec-4c71-a335-8551060a2f3b\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"ee4b6906-50ec-4c71-a335-8551060a2f3b\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"sessionId\":\"cc5ed6bd-0c2c-4c91-94f7-7c18e3bda941\",\"version\":\"2.1.70\",\"gitBranch\":\"alex/trails-multi-pr\",\"slug\":\"jazzy-inventing-fern\",\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"stop_hook_summary\",\"hookCo